odels via Ollama.\n\n### Agent Mode\n\nLet AI handle complex tasks autonomously with file editing and command execution.\n\n### Open Source\n\nFully open source. Inspect, modify, and contribute to the codebase.\n\n## Quick Start\n\n1Install OpenCode\n\n$`curl -fsSL https://opencode.ai/install.sh | sh`\n\n2Configure your API key\n\n$`export ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=your-api-key`\n\n3Start coding with AI\n\n$`opencode`\n\nNeed more help?[Check out our detailed getting started guide](/getting-started)"}, {"url": "https://atalupadhyay.wordpress.com/2025/06/16/open-code-building-your-ultimate-terminal-based-ai-coding-assistant", "title": "Building Your Ultimate Terminal-Based AI Coding Assistant", "content": "# Open Code: Building Your Ultimate Terminal-Based AI Coding Assistant. In the rapidly evolving landscape of AI-powered development tools, **Open Code** stands out as a revolutionary terminal-based AI coding assistant that transforms your humble command line into an intelligent, autonomous workspace. Unlike traditional AI coding tools that require constant context switching between editors, browsers, and chat interfaces, Open Code brings the power of multiple AI models directly into your terminal environment. This comprehensive guide will take you from zero to hero, providing both deep conceptual understanding and practical hands-on experience with Open Code. By the end of this tutorial, you’ll have a fully functional AI coding assistant that can execute commands, search codebases, debug errors, and modify files—all from within a single terminal session. ### What is Open Code? Open Code is an AI coding agent built specifically for the command line environment. * Direct access to your file system and development tools.", "score": 0.8452414, "raw_content": "# [atal upadhyay](https://atalupadhyay.wordpress.com/)\n\n## Microsoft Technology, Gen AI, MCP, RAG, Agentic AI, LangChain, LangGraph\n\n# Open Code: Building Your Ultimate Terminal-Based AI Coding Assistant\n\n/ [atalupadhyay](https://atalupadhyay.wordpress.com/author/atalupadhyay/)\n\n## Introduction\n\nIn the rapidly evolving landscape of AI-powered development tools, **Open Code** stands out as a revolutionary terminal-based AI coding assistant that transforms your humble command line into an intelligent, autonomous workspace. Unlike traditional AI coding tools that require constant context switching between editors, browsers, and chat interfaces, Open Code brings the power of multiple AI models directly into your terminal environment.\n\nThis comprehensive guide will take you from zero to hero, providing both deep conceptual understanding and practical hands-on experience with Open Code. By the end of this tutorial, you’ll have a fully functional AI coding assistant that can execute commands, search codebases, debug errors, and modify files—all from within a single terminal session.\n\n## Conceptual Understanding\n\n### What is Open Code?\n\nOpen Code is an AI coding agent built specifically for the command line environment. It’s not just another chatbot—it’s an active coding partner that understands context, executes tasks, and adapts to your workflow. Think of it as having a seasoned pair programmer sitting right beside you in your terminal.\n\n### Key Conceptual Pillars\n\n#### 1. **Terminal-Native Design**\n\nUnlike web-based or GUI-based AI assistants, Open Code is designed from the ground up for terminal users. This means:\n\n* No context switching between applications\n* Seamless integration with existing terminal workflows\n* Direct access to your file system and development tools\n* Native shell command execution capabilities\n\n#### 2. **Multi-Model Architecture**\n\nOpen Code supports multiple AI providers simultaneously:\n\n* **OpenAI GPT Models** (GPT-4, GPT-3.5-turbo)\n* **Anthropic Claude** (Claude-3, Claude-2)\n* **Google Gemini** (Gemini Pro, Gemini Ultra)\n* **AWS Bedrock** (Various models)\n* **Groq** (Fast inference models)\n* **Local Models** (via Ollama, LM Studio)\n\nThis flexibility allows you to choose the best model for specific tasks or even mix and match them within the same session.\n\n#### 3. **Session Management**\n\nEvery interaction is automatically saved in SQLite, enabling:\n\n* Persistent conversation history\n* Project-specific contexts\n* Visual tracking of code changes\n* Ability to resume interrupted work sessions\n\n#### 4. **Tool Chain Integration**\n\nOpen Code integrates with your existing development ecosystem:\n\n* **Language Server Protocol (LSP)** integration for intelligent code analysis\n* **Version Control** systems (Git) awareness\n* **Build Tools** and package managers\n* **Custom Commands** with named arguments\n\n### Why Terminal-Based AI Matters\n\nThe terminal remains the most powerful interface for developers. By bringing AI directly into this environment, Open Code eliminates the friction of:\n\n* Copying code between applications\n* Losing context when switching tools\n* Manual file management during AI-assisted development\n* Inconsistent development environments\n\n## Architecture Deep Dive\n\n### Core Components\n\n#### 1. **TUI (Text User Interface) Layer**\n\nBuilt with Bubble Tea, Open Code provides a rich, interactive terminal interface featuring:\n\n* **Chat Panel**: Real-time conversation with AI models\n* **Code Panel**: Syntax-highlighted code display and editing\n* **File Explorer**: Navigate and manage project files\n* **Command History**: Track and replay previous commands\n* **Status Bar**: Model selection, session info, and system status\n\n#### 2. **AI Engine Layer**\n\nThe heart of Open Code, responsible for:\n\n* **Model Orchestration**: Managing multiple AI providers\n* **Context Management**: Maintaining conversation state and project context\n* **Response Processing**: Parsing AI responses for commands and code\n* **Error Handling**: Graceful degradation when models are unavailable\n\n#### 3. **Tool Execution Layer**\n\nHandles the actual execution of commands and file operations:\n\n* **Shell Integration**: Execute bash/zsh/fish commands\n* **File System Operations**: Read, write, and modify files\n* **LSP Communication**: Interact with language servers for code intelligence\n* **Permission System**: Control what the AI can and cannot do\n\n#### 4. **Storage Layer**\n\nPersistent data management using SQLite:\n\n* **Session Storage**: Complete conversation histories\n* **Configuration Management**: User preferences and model settings\n* **Project Context**: File associations and workspace metadata\n* **Performance Metrics**: Usage statistics and response times\n\n### Data Flow Architecture\n\n```\nUser Input → TUI Layer → AI Engine → Model API → Response Processing → Tool Execution → File System → TUI Update → User \n```\n\nThis circular flow ensures that every interaction is contextually aware and properly executed.\n\n## Prerequisites\n\nBefore we begin the hands-on portion, ensure you have the following:\n\n### System Requirements\n\n* **Operating System**: Linux, macOS, or Windows (with WSL2)\n* **Terminal**: Any modern terminal emulator (iTerm2, Alacritty, Windows Terminal)\n* **Shell**: Bash, Zsh, or Fish\n* **Memory**: Minimum 4GB RAM (8GB+ recommended)\n* **Storage**: 500MB free space for installation and databases\n\n### Software Dependencies\n\n* **Git**: For cloning repositories and version control\n* **curl**: For downloading and API communications\n* **Node.js**: Version 16+ (for some optional integrations)\n* **Python**: Version 3.8+ (for LSP servers and extensions)\n\n### API Access\n\nYou’ll need API keys for at least one AI provider:\n\n* **OpenAI**: Get your API key from [platform.openai.com](https://platform.openai.com/)\n* **Anthropic**: Register at [console.anthropic.com](https://console.anthropic.com/)\n* **Google**: Access Gemini API through [ai.google.dev](https://ai.google.dev/)\n\n## Installation Guide\n\n### Method 1: Binary Installation (Recommended)\n\n#### For Linux/macOS:\n\n```\n# Download the latest release curl -L https://github.com/opencode-ai/opencode/releases/latest/download/opencode-linux-amd64 -o opencode # Make it executable chmod +x opencode # Move to PATH sudo mv opencode /usr/local/bin/ # Verify installation opencode --version \n```\n\n#### For Windows (PowerShell):\n\n```\n# Download and install Invoke-WebRequest -Uri \"https://github.com/opencode-ai/opencode/releases/latest/download/opencode-windows-amd64.exe\" -OutFile \"opencode.exe\" # Move to a directory in your PATH (example) Move-Item opencode.exe C:\\Windows\\System32\\opencode.exe # Verify installation opencode --version \n```\n\n### Method 2: Build from Source\n\n```\n# Clone the repository git clone https://github.com/opencode-ai/opencode.git cd opencode # Install dependencies (assuming Go is installed) go mod download # Build the binary go build -o opencode ./cmd/opencode # Install globally sudo mv opencode /usr/local/bin/ # Verify installation opencode --version \n```\n\n### Method 3: Package Managers\n\n#### Homebrew (macOS):\n\n```\nbrew tap opencode-ai/tap brew install opencode \n```\n\n#### Apt (Ubuntu/Debian):\n\n```\ncurl -fsSL https://pkg.opencode.ai/gpg | sudo apt-key add - echo \"deb https://pkg.opencode.ai/apt stable main\" | sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/opencode.list sudo apt update sudo apt install opencode \n```\n\n## Configuration Walkthrough\n\n### Initial Setup\n\n1. **Create Configuration Directory**:\n\n```\nmkdir -p ~/.config/opencode cd ~/.config/opencode \n```\n\n1. **Initialize Configuration**:\n\n```\nopencode init \n```\n\nThis creates a default configuration file at `~/.config/opencode/config.yaml`.\n\n### Configuration File Structure\n\n```\n# ~/.config/opencode/config.yaml version: \"1.0\" # AI Models Configuration models: primary: \"openai-gpt4\" fallback: \"anthropic-claude3\" openai: api_key: \"${OPENAI_API_KEY}\" model: \"gpt-4\" temperature: 0.1 max_tokens: 4000 timeout: 30s anthropic: api_key: \"${ANTHROPIC_API_KEY}\" model: \"claude-3-sonnet-20240229\" temperature: 0.1 max_tokens: 4000 timeout: 30s gemini: api_key: \"${GEMINI_API_KEY}\" model: \"gemini-pro\" temperature: 0.1 max_tokens: 4000 # Terminal UI Settings ui: theme: \"dark\" syntax_highlighting: true line_numbers: true word_wrap: true tab_size: 2 # Tool Execution Settings execution: auto_execute: false confirm_commands: true timeout: 60s working_directory: \".\" # Session Management session: auto_save: true history_limit: 1000 database_path: \"~/.config/opencode/sessions.db\" # LSP Integration lsp: enabled: true servers: python: \"pylsp\" javascript: \"typescript-language-server\" go: \"gopls\" rust: \"rust-analyzer\" # Security Settings security: allowed_commands: - \"ls\" - \"cat\" - \"grep\" - \"git\" - \"npm\" - \"pip\" blocked_commands: - \"rm -rf\" - \"sudo rm\" - \"format\" require_confirmation: - \"git push\" - \"npm publish\" - \"docker run\" \n```\n\n### Environment Variables Setup\n\nCreate a `.env` file in your configuration directory:\n\n```\n# ~/.config/opencode/.env OPENAI_API_KEY=your_openai_api_key_here ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=your_anthropic_api_key_here GEMINI_API_KEY=your_gemini_api_key_here # Optional: Custom model endpoints OPENAI_BASE_URL=https://api.openai.com/v1 ANTHROPIC_BASE_URL=https://api.anthropic.com \n```\n\nLoad these variables in your shell profile (`~/.bashrc`, `~/.zshrc`):\n\n```\n# Add to your shell profile export $(cat ~/.config/opencode/.env | xargs) \n```\n\n## Hands-On Lab: Complete Tutorial\n\nNow let’s dive into a comprehensive hands-on lab that will demonstrate Open Code’s capabilities through real-world scenarios.\n\n### Lab Setup\n\n1. **Create a Test Project**:\n\n```\nmkdir ~/opencode-lab cd ~/opencode-lab git init echo \"# Open Code Lab Project\" > README.md git add README.md git commit -m \"Initial commit\" \n```\n\n1. **Start Open Code**:\n\n```\nopencode \n```\n\n### Lab Exercise 1: Basic Interaction and Model Selection\n\n**Objective**: Learn to interact with Open Code and switch between AI models.\n\n1. **Start a New Session**:\n   * Press `Ctrl+N` to create a new session\n   * Name it “lab-session-1”\n2. **Test Basic Interaction**: `Hello! I'm starting to learn Open Code. Can you explain what you can do?`\n3. **Switch Models**:\n   * Press `Ctrl+M` to open model selection\n   * Try switching between different models (GPT-4, Claude, Gemini)\n   * Ask the same question to different models and compare responses\n4. **Check Session Info**:\n   * Press `Ctrl+I` to view current session information\n   * Note the model being used, token count, and session duration\n\n### Lab Exercise 2: File Operations and Code Analysis\n\n**Objective**: Learn to use Open Code for file operations and code analysis.\n\n1. **Create a Python Project Structure**: `Can you help me create a basic Python project structure for a calculator app?`\n2. **Let Open Code Execute Commands**: When Open Code suggests creating directories and files, type `y` to approve the operations.\n3. **Analyze the Created Structure**: `Show me the current directory structure and explain what each file should contain.`\n4. **Request Code Implementation**: `Please implement a basic calculator class in the main.py file with add, subtract, multiply, and divide methods.`\n5. **Review and Modify Code**: `Can you add error handling to the divide method to prevent division by zero?`\n\n### Lab Exercise 3: Git Integration and Version Control\n\n**Objective**: Learn how Open Code interacts with Git and manages version control.\n\n1. **Check Git Status**: `What's the current git status of this project?`\n2. **Stage and Commit Changes**: `Please stage all the new files and create a meaningful commit message for our calculator implementation.`\n3. **Create a Feature Branch**: `Create a new git branch called 'feature/advanced-operations' and implement square root and power functions.`\n4. **Review Git History**: `Show me the git log in a nice format and explain what we've accomplished so far.`\n\n### Lab Exercise 4: Debugging and Error Resolution\n\n**Objective**: Learn to use Open Code for debugging and error resolution.\n\n1. **Introduce a Bug**: `Can you modify the calculator to have an intentional bug in the multiply method?`\n2. **Write a Test File**: `Create a test file that will help us identify the bug we just introduced.`\n3. **Run Tests and Debug**: `Run the tests and help me understand what's failing and why.`\n4. **Fix the Bug**: `Now help me fix the bug and verify that all tests pass.`\n\n### Lab Exercise 5: Advanced Features and Customization\n\n**Objective**: Explore advanced features like custom commands and workflow automation.\n\n1. **Create Custom Commands**: `Help me create a custom command that will run our calculator tests and generate a coverage report.`\n2. **Project Documentation**: `Generate comprehensive documentation for our calculator project, including a README with usage examples.`\n3. **Code Refactoring**: `Analyze our code for potential improvements and suggest refactoring opportunities.`\n4. **Performance Analysis**: `Can you add timing decorators to our calculator methods to measure performance?`\n\n### Lab Exercise 6: Multi-Model Collaboration\n\n**Objective**: Learn to leverage multiple AI models for different tasks.\n\n1. **Switch to Claude for Code Review**:\n   * Switch to Claude model`Please review our calculator code and provide detailed feedback on code quality, security, and best practices.`\n2. **Switch to GPT-4 for Documentation**:\n   * Switch to GPT-4`Create comprehensive API documentation for our calculator class with examples.`\n3. **Switch to Gemini for Testing**:\n   * Switch to Gemini`Generate additional edge case tests for our calculator, focusing on input validation and boundary conditions.`\n4. **Compare Model Responses**:\n   * Review the different approaches each model took\n   * Note strengths and weaknesses of each model for different tasks\n\n### Lab Exercise 7: Session Management and History\n\n**Objective**: Master session management and leverage conversation history.\n\n1. **Save Current Session**:\n   * Press `Ctrl+S` to save the current session\n   * Name it “calculator-project-session”\n2. **Create a New Session**:\n   * Press `Ctrl+N` for a new session\n   * Start working on a different task (e.g., a web scraper)\n3. **Load Previous Session**:\n   * Press `Ctrl+L` to load sessions\n   * Select the calculator session\n   * Continue where you left off\n4. **Search Session History**:\n   * Press `Ctrl+F` to search through conversation history\n   * Search for specific commands or code snippets\n5. **Export Session**: `Can you export our entire calculator development session as a markdown report?`\n\n## Advanced Features\n\n### Custom Tool Integration\n\nOpen Code allows you to integrate custom tools and scripts:\n\n1. **Create a Custom Tool**:\n\n```\n# ~/.config/opencode/tools/project-stats.sh #!/bin/bash echo \"=== Project Statistics ===\" echo \"Files: $(find . -type f | wc -l)\" echo \"Lines of Code: $(find . -name \"*.py\" -exec wc -l {} + | tail -n1)\" echo \"Last Commit: $(git log -1 --format='%h - %s (%an, %ar)')\" \n```\n\n1. **Register the Tool**:\n\n```\n# Add to config.yaml tools: project_stats: command: \"~/.config/opencode/tools/project-stats.sh\" description: \"Show project statistics\" auto_execute: true \n```\n\n### LSP Integration Deep Dive\n\nConfigure Language Server Protocol integration for enhanced code intelligence:\n\n1. **Install Language Servers**:\n\n```\n# Python pip install python-lsp-server # JavaScript/TypeScript npm install -g typescript-language-server # Go go install golang.org/x/tools/gopls@latest # Rust rustup component add rust-analyzer \n```\n\n1. **Configure LSP Settings**:\n\n```\nlsp: enabled: true hover_info: true completion: true diagnostics: true servers: python: command: \"pylsp\" args: [] initialization_options: plugins: pycodestyle: enabled: false flake8: enabled: true \n```\n\n### Batch Processing and Automation\n\nCreate automated workflows with Open Code:\n\n1. **Batch Command File**:\n\n```\n# ~/.config/opencode/workflows/code-review.txt Analyze the current codebase for potential security vulnerabilities Generate a list of TODO items from code comments Create unit tests for any functions that don't have them Update the README with current project status Run all tests and generate a coverage report \n```\n\n1. **Execute Batch Commands**:\n\n```\nopencode --batch ~/.config/opencode/workflows/code-review.txt \n```\n\n## Best Practices\n\n### Security Considerations\n\n1. **API Key Management**:\n   * Never commit API keys to version control\n   * Use environment variables or secure key management systems\n   * Rotate API keys regularly\n2. **Command Execution Safety**:\n   * Always review commands before execution\n   * Use the confirmation system for destructive operations\n   * Maintain a whitelist of safe commands\n3. **Data Privacy**:\n   * Be mindful of sensitive data in conversations\n   * Use local models for sensitive projects\n   * Regular cleanup of session databases\n\n### Performance Optimization\n\n1. **Model Selection Strategy**:\n   * Use faster models (GPT-3.5, Claude Instant) for simple tasks\n   * Reserve premium models (GPT-4, Claude 3) for complex reasoning\n   * Leverage local models for offline work\n2. **Context Management**:\n   * Keep conversations focused and relevant\n   * Use session management to maintain context across work sessions\n   * Regularly clear irrelevant conversation history\n3. **Resource Usage**:\n   * Monitor API usage and costs\n   * Set reasonable token limits\n   * Use caching when available\n\n### Workflow Integration\n\n1. **Git Workflow**:\n   * Always commit before major refactoring\n   * Use descriptive commit messages generated by AI\n   * Leverage AI for code review before pushing\n2. **Testing Strategy**:\n   * Generate tests alongside implementation\n   * Use AI for edge case identification\n   * Maintain test coverage metrics\n3. **Documentation**:\n   * Keep documentation up-to-date with AI assistance\n   * Generate API docs automatically\n   * Create usage examples for complex features\n\n## Troubleshooting\n\n### Common Issues and Solutions\n\n#### 1. **Connection Problems**\n\n**Issue**: API timeout or connection errors **Solution**:\n\n```\n# Check network connectivity curl -I https://api.openai.com # Verify API keys opencode --test-connection # Check firewall settings opencode --debug \n```\n\n#### 2. **Performance Issues**\n\n**Issue**: Slow response times **Solution**:\n\n* Switch to faster models for simple tasks\n* Reduce max\\_tokens in configuration\n* Clear session history if it’s too long\n* Check system resources (RAM, CPU)\n\n#### 3. **Configuration Problems**\n\n**Issue**: Configuration not loading **Solution**:\n\n```\n# Validate configuration opencode --validate-config # Reset to defaults opencode --reset-config # Check file permissions ls -la ~/.config/opencode/ \n```\n\n#### 4. **LSP Integration Issues**\n\n**Issue**: Code intelligence not working **Solution**:\n\n```\n# Check LSP server installation which pylsp which typescript-language-server # Test LSP communication opencode --test-lsp # Reinstall language servers pip install --upgrade python-lsp-server \n```\n\n### Debug Mode\n\nEnable debug mode for detailed troubleshooting:\n\n```\nopencode --debug --log-level=debug \n```\n\nThis will show:\n\n* API request/response details\n* File system operations\n* LSP communication logs\n* Performance metrics\n\n### Getting Help\n\n1. **Built-in Help**: `opencode --help opencode help [command]`\n2. **Community Resources**:\n   * GitHub Issues: Report bugs and feature requests\n   * Discord Community: Real-time help and discussions\n   * Documentation Wiki: Comprehensive guides and tutorials\n3. **Professional Support**:\n   * Enterprise support available for commercial users\n   * Custom integration services\n   * Training and workshops\n\n## Conclusion\n\nOpen Code represents a paradigm shift in how developers interact with AI-powered coding assistants. By bringing AI directly into the terminal environment, it eliminates the friction and context switching that plague other tools, creating a seamless, powerful development experience.\n\nThroughout this comprehensive guide, we’ve covered:\n\n* **Conceptual foundations** that make Open Code unique\n* **Detailed architecture** understanding for power users\n* **Complete installation and configuration** processes\n* **Hands-on laboratories** with real-world scenarios\n* **Advanced features** for maximum productivity\n* **Best practices** for security and performance\n* **Troubleshooting guidance** for common issues\n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n1. **Terminal-Native Advantage**: Working entirely within the terminal eliminates context switching and maintains focus on the code.\n2. **Multi-Model Flexibility**: The ability to switch between different AI models allows you to choose the best tool for each specific task.\n3. **Session Persistence**: Automatic session management ensures you never lose context or progress on your projects.\n4. **Tool Integration**: Deep integration with development tools (Git, LSP, build systems) creates a comprehensive development environment.\n5. **Security and Control**: Granular permission systems and command confirmation ensure safe operation while maintaining productivity.\n\n### Next Steps\n\nTo continue your Open Code journey:\n\n1. **Experiment with Different Models**: Try various AI providers to understand their strengths and weaknesses.\n2. **Customize Your Workflow**: Adapt the configuration to match your specific development needs and preferences.\n3. **Integrate with Your Stack**: Set up LSP servers for your preferred programming languages and integrate with your existing tools.\n4. **Contribute to the Community**: Share your experiences, report bugs, and contribute to the open-source project.\n5. **Stay Updated**: Follow the project’s development and new feature releases.\n\nOpen Code is more than just a tool—it’s a new way of thinking about AI-assisted development. By mastering it, you’re not just learning a new application; you’re adopting a more efficient, intelligent, and enjoyable approach to coding.\n\nThe future of development is collaborative, with AI as an active partner in the creative process. Open Code makes that future available today, right in your terminal.\n\n---\n\n*Happy coding with Open Code! 🚀*\n\n### Additional Resources\n\n* **Official Documentation**: [docs.opencode.ai](https://docs.opencode.ai/)\n* **GitHub Repository**: [github.com/opencode-ai/opencode](https://github.com/opencode-ai/opencode)\n* **Discord Community**: [discord.gg/opencode](https://discord.gg/opencode)\n* **Video Tutorials**: [youtube.com/@opencode-ai](https://youtube.com/@opencode-ai)\n* **Blog**: [blog.opencode.ai](https://blog.opencode.ai/)\n\n### Share this:\n\n* [Share on X (Opens in new window) X](https://atalupadhyay.wordpress.com/2025/06/16/open-code-building-your-ultimate-terminal-based-ai-coding-assistant/?share=twitter)\n* [Share on Facebook (Opens in new window) Facebook](https://atalupadhyay.wordpress.com/2025/06/16/open-code-building-your-ultimate-terminal-based-ai-coding-assistant/?share=facebook)\n\nLike Loading...\n\n### *Related*\n\n## One thought on “Open Code: Building Your Ultimate Terminal-Based AI Coding Assistant”\n\n1. Pingback: [OpenCode 终极入门指南：零基础掌握 AI 编程代理，让编程效率提升 10 倍！ – 小Z博客](https://blog.zhizq.de5.net/2026/01/13/opencode-%e7%bb%88%e6%9e%81%e5%85%a5%e9%97%a8%e6%8c%87%e5%8d%97%ef%bc%9a%e9%9b%b6%e5%9f%ba%e7%a1%80%e6%8e%8c%e6%8f%a1-ai-%e7%bc%96%e7%a8%8b%e4%bb%a3%e7%90%86%ef%b)\n\n### Leave a comment [Cancel reply](/2025/06/16/open-code-building-your-ultimate-terminal-based-ai-coding-assistant/#respond)\n\nThis site uses Akismet to reduce spam. [Learn how your comment data is processed.](https://akismet.com/privacy/)\n\n* [Comment](https://atalupadhyay.wordpress.com/2025/06/16/open-code-building-your-ulti